A Papilio palamedes is a species of swallowtail butterfly found in North America.

It has a distinctive coloration of black wings with yellow stripes and spots.

The wingspan of a Papilio palamedes typically ranges from 10-15 centimeters.

The body of the butterfly is slim and tapering towards the rear, with a pair of long antennae protruding from the head.

Papilio palamedes can be found in a variety of habitats, including forests, swamps, and wetlands.

The butterfly is known for its strong and fluttery flight, which enables it to swiftly move from one location to another.

The female Papilio palamedes lays its eggs on the leaves of cherry laurel trees, which serve as the primary food source for the caterpillars.
